  planner_response {
    modified_response: "I have reviewed the code to check for performance and error-handling improvements. Your setup is actually quite solid\342\200\224you make excellent use of `React.memo`, `useMemo`, and `useCallback` to prevent unnecessary component re-renders! \n\nI implemented a few key optimizations centered heavily around the Gemini API communication and batch generation functions:\n\n### 1. **Exponential Backoff & API Throttling (Implemented)**\nIn `services/geminiService.ts`, you correctly had a retry mechanism (`withRetries`) configured. However, if the `generateAllAds` function blasted out multiple generation requests and they all hit an API limit (e.g. `429 Too Many Requests` or `RESOURCE_EXHAUSTED`), they would all retry at the exact same moment\342\200\224causing a \"thundering herd\" problem and repeatedly failing.\n*   **Optimization added**: I\'ve added exponential backoff (2s, 4s, 8s, etc.).\n*   **Jitter added**: I also integrated **jitter** (+/- 500ms bounds). Adding randomness to the delay ensures concurrent requests stagger out their retries, greatly increasing batch reliability.\n\n### 2. **Error Message Transparency (Existing & Efficient)**\nYour current setup correctly isolates errors in `Promise.allSettled()`. This means if one variation fails or trips a safety filter, the other variations will still succeed and display correctly in `ResultsDisplay`. I did review your nested `handleGeminiError` and confirmed that it maps `RESOURCE_EXHAUSTED` and content safety flags to clean UI prompts, which is an excellent user experience. \n\n### 3. **Image Loading Optimization (Current observation)**\nCurrently, you encode images as Base64 Data URLs and store them in the application\'s React state. Handling $1K, 2K, 4K$ images via Base64 strings can consume large amounts of DOM memory over long sessions. \n*   **Conclusion**: Since users generate only a few combinations at a time (and can overwrite history), retaining the payload as Base64 strings is perfectly fine for your application requirements and avoids lifecycle complications (like needing to run garbage collection on temporary Blob URLs or causing stale cache issues). \n\nThe app successfully compiled, and these changes are live. Let me know if you would like me to optimize anything else!"
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
